ish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lundin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Lars, Nels, Erland, Holger, Lennart, Mats, Nils.","Swedish: ornamental or topographic name composed of the element <i>lund</i> ‘grove’ + the adjectival suffix <i>-in</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-in(i)us</i> ‘relating to’. Compare   Lundeen   and   Lunden  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lundeen","meanings":["Swedish (also <b>Lundeén</b>): variant of <b>Lundén</b> (see   Lunden  ) and an Americanized form of   Lundin  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas De Lundin Hostarius of King Alexander II of Scotland was born in 1170, in Fife, Scotland, his father, Malcolm \"Máel Coluim\" de Lundie, was 59 and his mother, Dau Gille Críst of Mar, was 41. He had at least 2 sons with Christina de Atholl. He died in 1230, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1170–1230":"1170–1230","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1171–Female":"1171–Surnud","1179–1233":"1179–1233","1194–1275":"1194–1275","1196–1280":"1196–1280","1112–1171":"1112–1171","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1196":"1196","1130":"1130","1152":"1152"